title: Approaches to Learning
subject: Early Learning Guidelines: Birth to Age 3 (2012-)

document.title: Illinois Early Learning Guidelines For Children Birth to Age Three

693E5376CEC34C4BA6347EE8B3345711.description:
Creates an art project and creates a simple story to accompany
the artwork

551CFF326F6643C8B48ECB170AC09787.description:
Expresses inventive ideas to peers while playing; becomes directive, e.g., “You will be the police officer and you have to wear
this.”

26EB7B3A054B4E48B85479AC7EFC4CE5.description:
Takes on familiar roles during play, e.g., cooks in the pretend
kitchen

0F58C638D8974058A113C7D8DB873477.description: Communicates in creative ways, e.g., plays with words by rhyming, chanting, or making up songs; uses movement and dance

7547009C70DE4E02B534265E7DE382DB.description:
Engages familiar adults in pretend play, e.g., hands the adult a
play cup and pretends to pour “tea” into it

C110B2299AED4C5D839DF04B98845D0B.description:
Engages in pretend play with familiar objects and experiences,
e.g., places baby doll in stroller and pushes the stroller

631F6C6E8756472FA8B412B08DE3878A.description:
Pretends one object is really another by using substitution, e.g.,
using a toy car to brush hair

CAA1756C10B3495FB2D58DA1BBF7979C.description:
Imitates actions of other people in a playful manner, e.g., wags
finger at baby doll and says, “no, no, no”

3D71290E8BA7411482D2752CC59FCD20.description:
Begins to use objects in new and unexpected ways, e.g., places a
basket on head

9BED973769EF4F939F137D3289647B50.description:
Spends increasing amounts of time exploring and learning about
objects, e.g., will attend to a new toy for longer periods of time
in order to make sense of it

C9BF2282891B492AAEFA07D78E563D6B.description: Uses objects as they’re intended to be used, e.g., rolls a toy car

68E7650107684DB1A00687BD356A078C.description: Imitates a peer’s actions, e.g., bangs on table with cup

F842EB6EEF6A495E96EF4DBA4EA7E99F.description:
Imitates sounds, movements, and facial expressions, e.g., moves
body up and down after caregiver initially moves in that manner

1F69984C908B4B47938AC34D5F6E116D.description: Reaches for objects in close proximity

1025EADC20934D7DB81F04B77F3B6BDE.description:
Actively explores new objects found in the environment by
touching, patting, and mouthing

AA991D6FD6B544939EF483271C6268E5.description: Observes materials, objects, and people with curiosity

C885E2B953314897888752239BF6848D.description:
Children demonstrate the ability to use creativity, inventiveness, and imagination to increase their understanding and
knowledge of the world.

D46208E416724BFDB6DD1C4F02AB6693.description:
Shows interest in completing routine tasks independently, e.g.,
zips up coat, puts on shoes

6089E9FB2AD04179AB745F3F0C2287E7.description:
Practices an activity many times in order to master it, even if
setbacks occur

B1B15516C7D94417B995A3ABF2FE7BD9.description: Attempts to try a difficult task for an increasing amount of time

BCEC175EB3BF468A876E914D38188168.description:
Makes choices based on preferences, and at times, in opposition
to adult choices, e.g., “No milk, want juice”

526EE47AAB1747418569DDBE32002CB4.description:
Demonstrates preferences for activities, e.g., reads with a
caregiver, plays at the sand table, prefers to sit by certain
caregivers

1D7B9CA0761E477EA37830D728B50FD6.description:
Repeats experiences he or she enjoys, e.g., says “more” after
reading his or her favorite book

FAEA8732008F49889A2EF63E26E1B630.description:
Engages for longer periods of time when trying to work through
tasks, e.g., fits puzzle pieces together

1C39E91E9BFB4C68A1B7ED39B4E1D427.description: Focuses for longer periods of time on activities

C2D5EF2457384C879F4D7276FD7535E2.description:
Demonstrates preferences, e.g., gestures to the bean bag and
says “no” when presented with something else

8A3D3174185344AD9359754EF682F4B3.description:
Begins to attempt assisting in self-help activities, e.g., feeding,
grooming

CDF6E724576D482D92CD8437C8262FCB.description:
Repeats activities over and over, e.g., successfully inserts all the
shape sorter’s pieces, dumps them out, and starts again

7D4DA471E97A4B7193CD471483323E4A.description:
Participates in back-and-forth interactions, e.g., plays peek-a-boo
with an adult

D45B166E3AB74C2F95806BAC84ED7077.description:
Indicates preferences by using nonverbal cues, e.g., turning
head, kicking feet

70B729CC7FDA438CB0E8012060CC1A2B.description: Repeats interesting actions over and over

DA125CD3DD9647E798E4B181978405D5.description: Focuses attention on sounds, people, and objects

F0D2CE549B9A462C89BFC055210C5A46.description: Establishes and sustains eye contact with caregiver(s)

BAFC2D7D96AE4FEAB00C76D96A45B5C3.description: Children demonstrate the ability to remain engaged in experiences and develop a sense of purpose and follow-through.

C2C5475FD2E449DCA1707B457FF35BFB.description:
Demonstrates eagerness and determination when problem-solving during new tasks, e.g., the child who pushes the
caregiver’s hand away and refuses help until he or she is
ready to ask for it

A7E05BDDD1BF4C3C83B32AE441B8A3C1.description:
Attempts to independently resolve social conflicts without
automatically running to the caregiver, e.g., tries to retrieve an
object that was taken away by a peer

40C4B38DA7694B639666E6F208873383.description: Joins in a new activity after cautiously observing at first

31FA7756F69A45FF9DF3CDF8B787442D.description:
Demonstrates confidence in abilities and achievements, e.g.,
cheers or claps when accomplishing a goal such as completing a
simple puzzle

7D63829F756A494E88166BC52D3DFB57.description: Seeks out assistance and reassurance from familiar others

5829B2AFD47849B48FAED3DBF66CB78A.description:
Plays and explores farther away from attachment figure; continues to “check in” for reassurance, e.g., plays across the room
and glances toward caregiver, then re-engages in playing

0853BC4756CC4A2091AE4C4EEC564EA9.description:
Uses trial and error to solve a problem, e.g., tries different
angles when attempting to place a shape in a shape sorter

E7CEA03772554810B5B29A258DF33E29.description: Becomes more intentional and confident when playing and interacting, e.g., grabs, pushes, throws

FD505BF4CA294878B16DB3076CE349F9.description: Begins to take great risks with little regard for danger, e.g., lunging off a couch to reach for an object

7EAED01CB26B41269C7CA3ADA25702B5.description:
Attempts new skills on his or her own while “checking in” with
a familiar adult, e.g., a new crawler begins to move, then turns
toward the caregiver for reassurance before crawling away

27423756716B419AB2FFE4A445E2E061.description:
Uses different approaches for accomplishing a simple task, e.g.,
reaching, kicking, vocalizing

8DB4EF54151A4223A3A62557DDB3C2F9.description:
Explores new objects with eagerness, e.g., squeals and/or
squeezes a toy

2E8D46E6FD1349CAB863211005460703.description:
Cries and/or uses body language to signal and get needs met,
e.g., averts gaze, arches back

9100645D38BE47F0B683ADD0248D9362.description: Children demonstrate a willingness to participate in new experiences and confidently engage in risk-taking.

77B5013B939842FD879E2179A1023E15.description:
Uses increasingly refined skills while solving problems, e.g.,
uses own napkin to clean up a spill without asking an adult for
help

9B790B216F3B4DA593F3939C8A6332E9.description: Shows pride when accomplishing a task

EF93126B11C647C185FE1F187CE61434.description:
Refuses assistance, e.g., calls for help but then pushes a hand
away

ADAAE3F7750946A2831A686829D145F5.description: Begins to solve problems with less trial and error

F905CD39236342BC825AAB36C51AC3B8.description: Asks for help from a caregiver when needed

F1950CAE2AE3448FA82915426575BFF8.description:
Uses communication to solve problems, e.g., runs out of glue
during an art project and gestures to a caregiver for more

0C4EC45406AD4DD9A10BEF04EF9B8445.description:
Uses objects in the environment to solve problems, e.g., uses a
pail to move numerous books to the other side of the room

CCBCC4160E624EBE85DBA6DBA424D4D4.description:
Increases ability to recognize and solve problems through active
exploration, play, and trial and error, e.g., tries inserting a shape
at different angles to make it fit in a sorter

D761647A4A1F459B801C196A6232DFF1.description:
Imitates a caregiver’s behavior to accomplish a task, e.g.,
attempts to turn a doorknob

E5A0337093C641749B73AD956B0E29B4.description:
Attempts a variety of physical strategies to reach simple goals,
e.g., pulls the string of a toy train to move it closer or crawls to
get a ball that has rolled away

3A476EDFE64C44AEA7F1629DE6E809A3.description:
Begins to recognize that certain actions will draw out certain
responses, e.g., laughing and smiling will often result in an adult
responding in the same manner

0CB979E1921846B290F7FE34B06A9BBD.description:
Repeats actions over and over again to figure out how an object
works

18F3656AEBAD4EE083BD9FF8B8629339.description:
Communicates the need for assistance through verbal and/or
nonverbal cues, e.g., pointing, reaching, vocalizing

B8C2E01C5D044E71BB02DCBFC3EC7FFC.description: Enjoys repeating actions, e.g., continues to drop toy from highchair after it is picked up by a caregiver or sibling

03CA368E7A3C4FA5990C56BCBDC4ADCF.description:
Focuses on getting a caregiver’s attention through the use of
sounds, cries, gestures, and facial expressions

3C2382A575414A27A892272A6446C195.description:
Children attempt a variety of strategies to accomplish tasks, overcome obstacles, and find solutions to tasks, questions,
and challenges.

70934E8A378E4805B9DEC12E05EFFA81.description: Participates in a broader array of experiences, e.g., outdoor jungle gyms, art projects

C9E1B1D6558848D78A16AEEF74A48070.description:
Asks questions while interacting with others, e.g., “why,” “what,”
“how”

943FC5C6F67742BFB31545B1DAA052E6.description:
Enjoys accomplishing simple goals, e.g., completing a puzzle,
blowing a bubble

006097393C40428FAC3C829737CAFACB.description: Experiments with different ways to use materials and objects

1C0A31935EE34C9FBA2E95DB7E352286.description: Initiates play with others, e.g., a grandparent, sibling, or teacher

25B8A3F8634144CBB620823AEE4253B8.description:
Engages in active exploration in new environments, e.g., walks
over to a toy shelf in an unfamiliar home or classroom

C6FA4B9B7D534A74B8C93E60C4A348A6.description:
Demonstrates an interest in new activities and a willingness to
try out new experiences

A5033A2F76594799ACDE60EA97E238A0.description:
Engages familiar adults in meaningful interactions, e.g., points
to favorite toy, brings a book over to be read

0B505DEE73FC4973A3A77B93D7B89A99.description:
Begins to demonstrate preferences for objects and/or materials,
e.g., selects a book to read when given options

F9836C1C1D8541DF8B3CF77CF70B09A4.description: Moves toward a new activity by crawling or walking

BB1199969FB14AC0B594E65636D0EDB2.description:
Uses familiar objects in new ways, e.g., places a toy basket on
head

1A4F7EBD4F684E8F8AA311514EA71965.description:
Demonstrates an interest in new objects by manipulating and
turning the object

BF2F2E43E7CE486C8933841BD5ABEF5B.description:
Participates in joint attention with caregiver(s), e.g., focuses on
the same object

FE5C40D5536B445D84B4DF8B63165B24.description:
Attempts to initiate interaction with others, e.g., smiles, reaches
for a caregiver

8DB40AE6B2914600BC61A547F79E8033.description:
Actively explores new objects found in the environment, e.g.,
touches, pats, and mouths

84E508088EED4AFA994EC0E1CE9A120C.description:
Shows interest in him- or herself, e.g., gazes at hands, places
feet in mouth

300E3F01BFFC4D1A9C05F757442F1502.description:
Observes the environment and people; tracks a toy as it moves
from one point to another

04D60803AF5F4B009003A97DC3131EA6.description: Children demonstrate interest and eagerness in learning about their world.
